    return false;
}
```
Reason:
This code only checks if the `header` is null, without validating the `X-XSRF-Token` stored in the cookie. This oversight allows a request to be processed even if the tokens do not match, creating a vulnerability to CSRF attacks.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
private boolean validateToken(String header, String cookie) {
    if (header == null || cookie == null || !header.equals(cookie)) {
        return false;
    }
```
Reason:
This modification adds a check to ensure that both the `header` and `cookie` are not null and that they match. This validation prevents the processing of requests with mismatched tokens, thereby mitigating the risk of CSRF attacks.

